[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026958&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026958&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


&gt; It sounds to me that there is an implementation (not protocol) bug to
&gt; which you are particularly sensitive because of your role in backing up
&gt; a lot of zones.  I can understand how for your situation you might want
&gt; to restrict data values to ameliorate the pain you feel (until BIND is
&gt; fixed), but it still doesn't sound to me like good advice for the
&gt; general case.

    Right -- I don't there's anything wrong with the protocol per se,
and I'm sympathetic to the argument that BIND doesn't do this as well
as one might like.

    On the other hand, I do think there's an issue of how often you expect
your backup server to check up on you.  I think calling it an implementation
bug is overstating the case.  At some point, any implementation will hit a
limit.  Perhaps JEEVES can stand having its primary servers hitting it every
5 minutes but what if everyone made the refresh time 5 seconds?  We need
some sort of agreement about how hard you push your backup servers.  As
a large backup site, I'm pushing for people to be nice to their (shared)
backup domain server.

Craig

